# React Component Patterns

## Server vs Client Components

- **Default to Server Components** (no directive needed)
- Use `'use client'` directive only when:
  - Component uses React hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, etc.)
  - Component uses browser APIs (`window`, `document`, etc.)
  - Component uses event handlers (`onClick`, `onChange`, etc.)
  - Component uses third-party libraries that require client-side rendering

```typescript
// ✅ Server Component (default)
export const About = () => {
  return <section>...</section>
}

// ✅ Client Component (when needed)
;('use client')

import { useState } from 'react'

export const Counter = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0)
  return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>
}
```

## Component Structure

- Use **named exports** for components: `export const ComponentName = () => {}`
- Use **PascalCase** for component names
- For memoized components, always set `displayName` for better debugging

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
export const Hero = () => {
  return <section>...</section>
}

// ✅ Correct (memoized)
const ProjectCard = React.memo<ProjectCardProps>(({ title }) => {
  return <div>{title}</div>
})

ProjectCard.displayName = 'ProjectCard'
export { ProjectCard }
```

## Component Props

- Define props using `type` (not `interface`)
- Use descriptive prop names
- Provide default values when appropriate

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
type ButtonProps = {
  label: string
  onClick: () => void
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary'
  disabled?: boolean
}

export const Button = ({
  label,
  onClick,
  variant = 'primary',
  disabled = false
}: ButtonProps) => {
  // ...
}
```

## React Imports

- Don't import `React` unless needed (e.g., for `React.memo`)
- Use named imports from React when possible

```typescript
// ✅ Correct (when React.memo is needed)
import React from 'react'

// ✅ Correct (when only hooks are needed)
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react'

// ❌ Incorrect
import React from 'react' // when not needed
```

## React Keys

- Use **stable, unique keys** - never use array index alone
- Prefer unique identifiers (e.g., `item.id`, `item.title`, `item.name`)
- Use composite keys when needed (e.g., `${item.title}-${item.date}`)

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
{
  items.map((item) => <div key={item.id}>{item.name}</div>)
}

{
  items.map((item) => (
    <div key={`${item.title}-${item.date}`}>{item.title}</div>
  ))
}

// ❌ Incorrect
{
  items.map((item, index) => <div key={index}>{item.name}</div>)
}
```
